# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: qt-quick-qml
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:qt-quick-qml/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:qt-quick-qml/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] QML elements can be augmented by standard JavaScript both inline and via included .js files.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Elements can also be seamlessly integrated and extended by C++ components using the Qt framework.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] QML is the language; its JavaScript runtime is the custom V4 engine, since Qt 5.2; and Qt Quick is the 2D scene graph and the UI framework based on it.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] These are all part of the Qt Declarative module, while the technology is no longer called Qt Declarative.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] QML and JavaScript code can be compiled into native C++ binaries with the Qt Quick Compiler.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Alternatively there is a QML cache file format which stores a compiled version of QML dynamically for faster startup the next time it is run.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Objects are specified by their type, followed by a pair of braces.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Object types always begin with a capital letter.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] In the example above, there are two objects, a Rectangle; and its child, an Image.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Between the braces, one can specify information about the object, such as its properties.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Properties are specified as property: value.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] In the example above, the Image has a property named `source`, which has been assigned the value `pics/logo.png`.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] The property and its value are separated by a colon.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Each object can be given a special unique property called an id.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Assigning an id enables the object to be referred to by other objects and scripts.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] The first Rectangle element below has an id, `myRect`.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] The second Rectangle element defines its own width by referring to `myRect.width`, which means it will have the same width value as the first Rectangle element.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] An id must begin with a lower-case letter or an underscore, and can contain no characters other than letters, digits, and underscores.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] A property binding specifies the value of a property in a declarative way.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] The property value is automatically updated if the other properties or data values change, following the reactive programming paradigm.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Property bindings are created implicitly in QML whenever a property is assigned a JavaScript expression.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] The following QML uses two property bindings to connect the size of the rectangle to that of otherItem.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] QML extends a standards-compliant JavaScript engine, so any valid JavaScript expression can be used as a property binding.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Bindings can access object properties, make function calls, and even use built-in JavaScript objects like Date and Math.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] States are a mechanism to combine changes to properties in a semantic unit.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] A button for example has a pressed and a non-pressed state, an address book application could have a read-only and an edit state for contacts.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Every element has an "implicit" base state.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Every other state is described by listing the properties and values of those elements which differ from the base state.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Example: In the default state, myRect is positioned at 0,0.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] In the "moved" state, it is positioned at 50,50.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Clicking within the mouse area changes the state from the default state to the "moved" state, thus moving the rectangle.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] State changes can be animated using Transitions.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Animations in QML are done by animating properties of objects.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Properties of type real, int, color, rect, point, size, and vector3d can all be animated.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] QML supports three main forms of animation: basic property animation, transitions, and property behaviors.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] The simplest form of animation is a PropertyAnimation, which can animate all of the property types listed above.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] A property animation can be specified as a value source using the Animation on property syntax.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] This is especially useful for repeating animations.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Usage of QML does not require Qt/C++ knowledge to use, but it can be easily extended via Qt.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Any C++ class derived from QObject can be easily registered as a type which can then be instantiated in QML.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Signal handlers are JavaScript callbacks which allow imperative actions to be taken in response to an event.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] All signal handler names begin with "on".
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Because QML and JavaScript are very similar, almost all code editors supporting JavaScript will work.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] Full support for syntax highlighting, code completion, integrated help, and a WYSIWYG editor are available in the free cross-platform integrated development environment (IDE) Qt Creator since version 2.1 and many other IDEs.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] The qml executable can be used to run a QML file as a script.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] If the QML file begins with a shebang it can be made directly executable.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qml] However packaging an application for deployment (especially on mobile platforms) generally involves writing a simple C++ launcher and packaging the needed QML files as resources.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] QML is a declarative language that allows user interfaces to be described in terms of their visual components and how they interact and relate with one another.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] It is a highly readable language that was designed to enable components to be interconnected in a dynamic manner, and it allows components to be easily reused and customized within a user interface.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] Using the `QtQuick` module, designers and developers can easily build fluid animated user interfaces in QML, and have the option of connecting these user interfaces to any back-end C++ libraries.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] The following Qt Academy courses are recommended for getting started with QML and Qt Quick.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] QML is a user interface specification and programming language.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] It allows developers and designers alike to create highly performant, fluidly animated and visually appealing applications.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] QML offers a highly readable, declarative, JSON-like syntax with support for imperative JavaScript expressions combined with dynamic property bindings.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] The QML language and engine infrastructure is provided by the Qt Qml module.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] For in-depth information about the QML language, see the Qt Qml module documentation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] Qt Quick is the standard library of QML types and functionality for QML.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] It includes visual types, interactive types, animations, models and views, particle effects and shader effects.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] A QML application developer can get access to all of that functionality with a single import statement.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] The `QtQuick` QML library is provided by the Qt Quick module.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] For in-depth information about the various QML types and other functionality provided by Qt Quick, please see the Qt Quick module documentation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] Qt Quick adds visual types, animation types, and other QML types in addition to the standard QML types from Qt Qml.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] For a set of UI controls, the Qt Quick Controls module implements several controls such as buttons, menus, and views.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] These controls come with several built-in styles that can be used, and also support the creation of custom styles.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] Qt Creator has built-in support for creating Qt Quick applications.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] Qt VS Tools and Qt Extension for VS Code also allow you to create Qt Quick applications with Visual Studio and Visual Studio Code.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] The QML Language Server can be used from any IDE supporting the language server protocol.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] For a design centric workflow, use Qt Design Studio.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] To learn more about uses of QML code, there are several code samples which show how QML types are used.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] In addition, there are several demos which show how QML code is used in applications.
