[src:qt-quick-qml/qmlapplications] All other trademarks are property of their respective owners.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qt-quick] Qt Declarative is a runtime interpreter that reads the *Qt declarative user interface definition*, QML data, and displays the UI that it describes.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qt-quick] The QML syntax allows using JavaScript to provide the logic, and it is often used for this purpose.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qt-quick] It is not the only way, however: logic can be written with native code as well.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qt-quick] Qt Quick and QML are officially supported in Qt 4.7 (with Qt Creator 2.1), and it is a commercial option in mobile applications when Qt 4.7 is available for deployment in Symbian and Maemo and MeeGo devices.
[src:qt-quick-qml/qt-quick] It is also the native language of Ubuntu Touch.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:qt-quick-qml/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] A **scene graph** is a hierarchical data structure commonly used by vector-based graphics editing applications and modern computer games, which cascades the inheritance or spatial representation of a set of objects.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] It is a collection of nodes in a graph or tree structure.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] A tree node may have many children but only a single parent, with the effect of a parent applied to all its child nodes; an operation performed on a group automatically propagates its effect to all of its members.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] In many programs, associating a geometrical transformation matrix (see also transformation and matrix) at each group level and concatenating such matrices together is an efficient and natural way to process such operations.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] A common feature, for instance, is the ability to group related shapes and objects into a compound object that can then be manipulated as easily as a single object.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] In vector-based graphics editing, each leaf node in a scene graph represents some atomic unit of the document, usually a shape such as an ellipse or Bezier path.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Although shapes themselves (particularly paths) can be decomposed further into nodes such as spline nodes, it is practical to think of the scene graph as composed of shapes rather than going to a lower level of representation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Another useful and user-driven node concept is the layer.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] A layer acts like a transparent sheet upon which any number of shapes and shape groups can be placed.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] The document then becomes a set of layers, any of which can be conveniently made invisible, dimmed, or locked (made read-only).
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Some applications place all layers in a linear list, while others support layers within layers to any desired depth.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Internally, there may be no real structural difference between layers and groups at all, since they are both just nodes of a scene graph.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] If differences are needed, a common type declaration in C++ would be to make a generic node class, and then derive layers and groups as subclasses.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] A visibility member, for example, would be a feature of a layer, but not necessarily of a group.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Scene graphs are useful for modern games using 3D graphics and increasingly large worlds or levels.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] In such applications, nodes in a scene graph (generally) represent entities or objects in the scene.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] For instance, a game might define a logical relationship between a knight and a horse so that the knight is considered an extension to the horse.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] The scene graph would have a 'horse' node with a 'knight' node attached to it.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] The scene graph may also describe the spatial, as well as the logical, relationship of the various entities: the knight moves through 3D space as the horse moves.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] In these large applications, memory requirements are major considerations when designing a scene graph.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] For this reason, many large scene graph systems use geometry instancing to reduce memory costs and increase speed.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] In our example above, each knight is a separate scene node, but the graphical representation of the knight (made up of a 3D mesh, textures, materials and shaders) is instanced.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] This means that only a single copy of the data is kept, which is then referenced by any 'knight' nodes in the scene graph.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] This allows a reduced memory budget and increased speed, since when a new knight node is created, the appearance data need not be duplicated.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] The simplest form of scene graph uses an array or linked list data structure, and displaying its shapes is simply a matter of linearly iterating the nodes one by one.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Other common operations, such as checking to see which shape intersects the mouse pointer are also done via linear searches.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] For small scene graphs, this tends to suffice.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Applying an operation on a scene graph requires some way of dispatching an operation based on a node's type.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] For example, in a render operation, a transformation group node would accumulate its transformation by matrix multiplication, vector displacement, quaternions or Euler angles.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] After which a leaf node sends the object off for rendering to the renderer.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Some implementations might render the object directly, which invokes the underlying rendering API, such as DirectX or OpenGL.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] But since the underlying implementation of the rendering API usually lacks portability, one might separate the scene graph and rendering systems instead.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] In order to accomplish this type of dispatching, several different approaches can be taken.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] In object-oriented languages such as C++, this can easily be achieved by virtual functions, where each represents an operation that can be performed on a node.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Virtual functions are simple to write, but it is usually impossible to add new operations to nodes without access to the source code.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Alternatively, the *visitor pattern* can be used.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] This has a similar disadvantage in that it is similarly difficult to add new node types.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Other techniques involve the use of RTTI (Run-Time Type Information).
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] The operation can be realised as a class that is passed to the current node; it then queries the node's type using RTTI and looks up the correct operation in an array of callbacks or functors.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] This requires that the map of types to callbacks or functors be initialized at runtime, but offers more flexibility, speed and extensibility.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Variations on these techniques exist, and new methods can offer added benefits.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] One alternative is scene graph rebuilding, where the scene graph is rebuilt for each of the operations performed.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] This, however, can be very slow, but produces a highly optimised scene graph.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] It demonstrates that a good scene graph implementation depends heavily on the application in which it is used.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Traversals are the key to the power of applying operations to scene graphs.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] At this point, many scene graph engines then traverse back up the tree, applying a similar operation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] For example, consider a render operation that takes transformations into account: while recursively traversing down the scene graph hierarchy, a pre-render operation is called.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] If the node is a transformation node, it adds its own transformation to the current transformation matrix.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Once the operation finishes traversing all the children of a node, it calls the node's post-render operation so that the transformation node can undo the transformation.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] This approach drastically reduces the necessary amount of matrix multiplication.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Some scene graph operations are actually more efficient when nodes are traversed in a different order – this is where some systems implement scene graph rebuilding to reorder the scene graph into an easier-to-parse format or tree.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] For example, in 2D cases, scene graphs typically render themselves by starting at the tree's root node and then recursively draw the child nodes.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] The tree's leaves represent the most foreground objects.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Since drawing proceeds from back to front with closer objects simply overwriting farther ones, the process is known as employing the Painter's algorithm.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] In 3D systems, which often employ depth buffers, it is more efficient to draw the closest objects first, since farther objects often need only be depth-tested instead of actually rendered, because they are occluded by nearer objects.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Bounding Volume Hierarchies (BVHs) are useful for numerous tasks – including efficient culling and speeding up collision detection between objects.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] A BVH is a spatial structure, but doesn't have to partition the geometry (see spatial partitioning below).
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] A BVH is a tree of bounding volumes (often spheres, axis-aligned bounding boxes or oriented bounding boxes).
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] At the bottom of the hierarchy, the size of the volume is just large enough to encompass a single object tightly (or possibly even some smaller fraction of an object in high resolution BVHs).
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] As one ascends the hierarchy, each node has its own volume that tightly encompasses all the volumes beneath it.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] At the root of the tree is a volume that encompasses all the volumes in the tree (the whole scene).
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] BVHs are useful for speeding up collision detection between objects.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] If an object's bounding volume does not intersect a volume higher in the tree, it cannot intersect any object below that node (so they are all rejected very quickly).
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] There are some similarities between BVHs and scene graphs.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] A scene graph can easily be adapted to include/become a BVH – if each node has a volume associated or there is a purpose-built "bound node" added in at convenient location in the hierarchy.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] This may not be the typical view of a scene graph, but there are benefits to including a BVH in a scene graph.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] An effective way of combining spatial partitioning and scene graphs is by creating a scene leaf node that contains the spatial partitioning data.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] This can increase computational efficiency of rendering.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Spatial data is usually static and generally contains non-moving scene data in some partitioned form.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Some systems may have the systems and their rendering separately.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] This is fine and there are no real advantages to either method.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] In particular, it is bad to have the scene graph contained within the spatial partitioning system, as the scene graph is better thought of as the grander system to the spatial partitioning.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Very large drawings, or scene graphs that are generated solely at runtime (as happens in ray tracing rendering programs), require defining of group nodes in a more automated fashion.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] A raytracer, for example, will take a scene description of a 3D model and build an internal representation that breaks up its individual parts into bounding boxes (also called bounding slabs).
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] These boxes are grouped hierarchically so that ray intersection tests (as part of visibility determination) can be efficiently computed.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] A group box that does not intersect an eye ray, for example, can entirely skip testing any of its members.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] A similar efficiency holds in 2D applications as well.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] If the user has magnified a document so that only part of it is visible on their computer screen, and then scrolls in it, it is useful to use a bounding box (or in this case, a bounding rectangle scheme) to quickly determine which scene graph elements are visible and thus actually need to be drawn.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Depending on the particulars of the application's drawing performance, a large part of the scene graph's design can be impacted by rendering efficiency considerations.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] In 3D video games such as Quake, binary space partitioning (BSP) trees are heavily favored to minimize visibility tests.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] BSP trees, however, take a very long time to compute from design scene graphs, and must be recomputed if the design scene graph changes, so the levels tend to remain static, and dynamic characters aren't generally considered in the spatial partitioning scheme.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Scene graphs for dense regular objects such as heightfields and polygon meshes tend to employ quadtrees and octrees, which are specialized variants of a 3D bounding box hierarchy.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Since a heightfield occupies a box volume itself, recursively subdividing this box into eight subboxes (hence the 'oct' in octree) until individual heightfield elements are reached is efficient and natural.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] PHIGS was the first commercial scene graph specification, and became an ANSI standard in 1988.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Disparate implementations were provided by Unix hardware vendors.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] The HOOPS 3D Graphics System appears to have been the first commercial scene graph library provided by a single software vendor.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] It was designed to run on disparate lower-level 2D and 3D interfaces, with the first major production version (v3.0) completed in 1991.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] Silicon Graphics (SGI) released OpenGL Performer or more commonly called Performer in 1991 which was the primary scenegraph system for most SGI products into the future.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] IRIS Inventor 1.0 (1992) was released by SGI, which was a high level scene graph built on top of Performer.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] It was followed up with Open Inventor in 1994, another iteration of the high level scene graph built on top of newer releases of Performer.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] More 3D scene graph libraries can be found in Category:3D scenegraph APIs.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] X3D is a royalty-free open standards file format and run-time architecture to represent and communicate 3D scenes and objects using XML.
[src:qt-quick-qml/scene-graph] It is an ISO-ratified standard that provides a system for the storage, retrieval and playback of real-time graphics content embedded in applications, all within an open architecture to support a wide array of domains and user scenarios.
